User-Agent: Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.0; Win64; x64; Trident/4.0; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; SLCC1; Media Center PC 5.0; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET4.0C; .NET CLR 3.0.30729) Build Identifier: Firefox 4.0
updated from version 3.1.6
installed extensions and themes I had been using in Firefox 3.1.6: Forecastfox Weather, AdBlockPlus, NoScript, LavaFox, FasterFirefox
used Firefox 4 with these installed, and experienced graphics corruption immediately
Reproducible: Always
Steps to Reproduce: 1.update Firefox 3.1.6 to Firefox 4 2.install extensions as noted above 3.restart Firefox Actual Results: graphics corruption, crashing not only Firefox, but any/all other applications i.e.:online/offline gaming
corrupted/crashed Nvidia GeForce Graphics Drivers (beta270.51) and NVidia OpenGL (ver 3.3)
Expected Results: worked as flawlessly as Firefox 3.1.6

Can you attach a Screenshot showing the Issue?
Does setting "gfx.direct2d.disabled" to "true" via "about:config" and restarting Firefox show a Difference?
Created attachment 524002 screenshot of failure as Firefox 4 starts up

Does setting "gfx.direct2d.disabled" to "true" via "about:config" and restarting Firefox show a Difference?
yes, it seems to have stopped the always-crashing/corrupting of Firefox 4
Ok, so this is a D2D Issue against the 270.51 Beta Driver. Does it also happen against the 267.24 Beta and/or 266.58 WHQL Driver too?
I rolled back Video Driver to version 266.58, and it behaved the same; yes
It's normal to have some issues on BETA drivers ;) Can be probably marked as RESOLVED INVALID, because it's driver bug.

virtual manpl: comment 6 indicates it happens with 266.58 which is supposedly whql per comment 5.
as for bugs involving third parties, we're trying to move to a system where we submit problems to vendors and track them here instead of simply saying 'not our fault'.
Created attachment 524926 shows how the system reacted to the OpenGL Driver failure

You should rather report it to nVidia ( http://nvidia.custhelp.com/cgi-bin/nvidia_submit.cfg/php/enduser/ask.php ) than here ;)
Also don't forget to mention and upload this files
"Files that help describe the problem WD-20110409-1850.dmp sysdata.xml Version.txt"

thanks much, but I'm covering ALL bases here... including the ones I've already crossed, in hopes that Mozilla will see that if not for their "bug", I would not have had this much "fun" trying to nail down problems affecting BOTH Firefox and NVidia
